==English==

===Etymology===
{{F.}} ''prime'', from {{L.}} ''[[primus]]'', first

===Pronunciation===
prīm, /praɪm/, /<tt>praIm</tt>/

===Adjective===
'''prime''' (''no {{compar}} or {{superl}}'')

#Of [[greatest]] [[importance]].
#:''Our prime concern here is to keep the community safe.''
#Of [[highest]] [[quality]].
#:''This is a prime location for a bookstore.''
#Used as a [[starting point]] or [[basis]].
#:''Both the English and French governments established prime meridians in their capitals.''
#{{algebra}} Of an [[integer]] or an element of certain [[mathematical structure]]s, having exactly two [[factor]]s, namely itself and the [[unit]] for that structure (1 in the case of integers).
#:''The element ''x<sup>2</sup> + 1'' is prime in this field.''
#[[Irreducible]] or [[absolute]]; that from which others are [[derived]]; [[fundamental]].

====Synonyms====
*(''of greatest importance''): [[great]]est, [[main]], most [[important]], [[primary]], [[top]]
*(''of highest quality''): [[top-quality]]
*(''used as a starting point or basis''):

===Noun===
'''prime''' (''plural'' '''primes''')

#(''algebra, [[number theory]]'')[[Category:Algebra]][[Category:Number theory]] A prime [[element]] of a [[mathematical structure]], particularly a [[prime number]].
#:''3 is a prime.''
#(''backgammon'') Six [[consecutive]] [[block]]s, which prevent the opponent's pieces from passing.
#:''I'm threatening to build a prime here.''

====Synonyms====
*(''algebra''): [[prime number]] (''when an integer'')

===Transitive verb===
'''to prime''' ('''primes''', '''priming''', '''primed''')

#To [[prepare]] a [[mechanism]] for its main [[work]].
#:''You'll have to press this button twice to prime the fuel pump.''
#To [[apply]] a [[coat]] of [[primer]] [[paint]] to.
#:''I need to prime these handrails before we can apply the finish coat.''

